		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Mereology</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>In <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophy</a>, <b>mereology</b> (from the Greek μερος meros part and the ending -logy study, discussion, science) is a collection of axiomatic <a href="/wiki/First-order_theories" title="First-order theories" class="mw-redirect">first-order theories</a> dealing with parts and their respective wholes. Mereology is both an application of <a href="/wiki/Predicate_logic" title="Predicate logic">predicate logic</a> and a branch of <a href="/wiki/Formal_ontology" title="Formal ontology">formal ontology</a>.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
